            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="border-top generic-devider-line" style="opacity: 0.75; margin-left: 10px"></div>
            <br />
        
            <h5 style="margin-left: 10px;">Best practices & Optimal usage</h5>
            <div style="margin-left: 15px;">
                <p>Here are some tips and tricks for using this app optimally</p>
                <ul>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Educations:</strong>
                        <p>It is recommended you create multiple educations for one education. This way you have different parts of your education separated for a better overview.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Descriptions:</strong>
                        <p>Descriptions are optional, but they can help you find your entries. It is recommended to always add a description. Descriptions do not have to be long, but they should properly describe your entry.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Institutions:</strong>
                        <p>You can add the name of the institute of your education. It is recommended you add this to your educations to better find your entries. Use the following convention for adding institutions. "SI, Some Institution"</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Data:</strong>
                        <p>It is recommended that you sometimes back up your data. You can do this by copying the file '<code>GradeMaster.db</code>' and save it somewhere at a dedicated location. The file is located at: '<code>C:\Users\YourUser\AppData\Local\GradeMaster\Data</code>'.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Search:</strong>
                        <p>When searching you can use following advanced patterns on following pages.</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Educations:</strong> Patterns: "#1 some text | #2 some text" this will search for everything matching (#1) and institution matching (2#). Example: "Something specific | Institute1". <br/>
                                It is also possible to search for only "completed" or "in progress" entries. (Currently search for completion state can't be used with other search) <br/>
                                Searching for the completion state is also possible now. In order to search for the completion state just add (complete) or (c) / (in progress) or (ip) at the end of your search.</li>
                            <li><strong>Subjects:</strong> Patterns: Supports the pattern of Educations Page, but also allows you to search for subject with a combination of the subject name and subject semester. Example: "Some name 3" or "Some name - 3". <br/>
                                It is also possible to combine this with the search of institution. Example: "Some name 3 | Institute1". <br />
                                It is also possible to search for only "completed" or "in progress" entries. (Currently search for completion state can't be used with other search) <br />
                                Searching for the completion state is also possible now. In order to search for the completion state just add (complete) or (c) / (in progress) or (ip) at the end of your search.
                            </li>
                            <li><strong>Grades:</strong> Pattern: Supports the same patterns as the Subject page search. <br/> Search with completion state is not possible on this page.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top: 100px;"></div>
</section>

